{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:11:23.168276", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network reachability snapshot\n\nScope and method\n- I analyzed the provided reachability/ping matrix (full results returned by the lab tool). No active remediation was performed. The goal was to detect anomalies, localize faulty devices/segments and identify likely root causes.\n\nExecutive summary — overall health\n- Overall the network is healthy for normal user-to-service traffic:\n  - User hosts across the 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 subnets can reach the infrastructure/services they need: DHCP (10.200.0.8), DNS (10.200.0.2), the published load balancer (10.200.0.7) and the front-end web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6). Ping results for these paths show 0% loss and low latencies (typical avg RTTs 1–5 ms).\n  - Server-farm internal connectivity among 10.200.x servers and between backend nodes (20.200.x) and the load balancer is working where expected (0% loss, low latency).\n- No widespread packet loss was observed on the tested paths marked “ok”.\n\nKey abnormal observations\n1. Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is not reachable from user hosts\n   - Pings from almost all user hosts to backend_web_0/1/2 (20.200.0.2–20.200.0.4) returned “unknown” (no ICMP responses).\n   - Many server-to-server pings involving addresses in 20.200.0.0/24 to/from 10.200.0.x are also marked “unknown” for certain pairs.\n   - This is consistent and widespread: it is not a single host failing but a class of addresses (20.200.0.x) that are not reachable from the user subnets.\n\n2. Selective reachability between 20.200.x and 10.200.x hosts\n   - The backend nodes (20.200.x) can reach each other (20.200 ↔ 20.200) and can reach the load_balancer (10.200.0.7). For example backend_web_2 -> backend_web_1 and backend_web_2 -> load_balancer are OK.\n   - However, pings between backend nodes (20.200.x) and several other 10.200 hosts (web_server_0..3, dns_server) are often “unknown” from the 20.200 side. This indicates selective or asymmetric reachability between the two IP spaces rather than a complete routing failure.\n\n3. Isolated latency spikes (minor)\n   - A few host→server paths show higher max RTTs and large RTT mdev (examples: host_1_1_1_2 -> web_server_3 with rtt_max 18.59 ms and mdev 6.62 ms; several other isolated high max values). These appear to be occasional spikes rather than sustained loss — no packet loss recorded.\n   - They are not widespread and show up on a small subset of tests.\n\nLocalization — where the behavior is observed and likely locus of control\n- Affected segments/devices:\n  - The isolation involves the backend network 20.200.0.0/24 and its interactions with the broader 10.200.0.0/24 server farm and user subnets.\n  - The behavior is consistent across all user hosts and many server hosts, so the control point is likely at the server-facing routing/segmentation point — i.e., the server_access_router (or an ACL/firewall logically colocated with it) or an interposing firewall between 10.200.x and 20.200.x.\n- Devices showing normal behavior:\n  - Core/distribution paths (user subnets ↔ DHCP, DNS, load_balancer, public web servers) appear healthy — routers and access switches for user traffic are not implicated by packet loss.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Intentional network segmentation / access-control policy:\n  - The most likely root cause for the observed “unknown” reachability to the 20.200.x backend addresses is an intentional access-control policy / ACL or segmentation that prevents direct access from user subnets (and possibly from many 10.200 hosts) to the backend network. The design notes explicitly state “by design the backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts,” which aligns with the observed lack of ICMP responses from 20.200.x.\n  - The selective allow (backends can reach load_balancer; backends can reach peer backends) and deny (hosts cannot reach backends; many 10.200 ↔ 20.200 pairs fail) pattern strongly suggests an enforcement point (ACL / firewall / VRF / policy-based routing) rather than a random routing fault.\n- Asymmetric or policy-based filtering:\n  - The selective nature (20.200 → load_balancer OK, but 20.200 → some 10.200 hosts unknown) could be due to finer-grained ACLs or host-based firewalls on specific 10.200 hosts, or asymmetric routing/VRF separation that prevents replies to certain sources. However, since user hosts can reach 10.200 web servers normally, host-level blocking on the 10.200 servers seems less likely than a centralized policy.\n- Routing misconfiguration (less likely given data):\n  - A routing-only fault would typically produce broader blackholing for an entire prefix. We see targeted reachability (20.200→load_balancer OK; user→10.200 OK) so a pure routing omission is less consistent with this pattern. That said, routing combined with policies could explain some asymmetric behaviors.\n\nRelevant additional findings (for completeness)\n- DHCP and DNS services are reachable from all user hosts tested (10.200.0.8 and 10.200.0.2 respectively), confirming service advertisement and reachability for required services.\n- No single router or switch reported total failure from reachability data; failures are policy/segment-specific.\n- No packet loss observed on the large majority of tested paths (all recorded \"ok\" results show 0% loss).\n\nConclusions\n- The network is functioning appropriately for user-facing services: hosts can obtain DHCP, resolve DNS and reach the published web service via the load balancer.\n- The non-reachability of the backend 20.200.0.0/24 network from hosts appears deliberate and consistently enforced by a segmentation/policy control point (likely the server_access_router or an attached firewall/ACL). This matches the stated design goal that backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts.\n- Some small, isolated latency spikes exist but are not causing packet loss and are not widespread.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic checks (if you want to proceed)\n- Inspect ACLs / firewall rules on server_access_router and any firewall appliance controlling the server farm (to confirm the policies that affect 20.200.0.0/24).\n- Query FRR/OSPF routing tables on server_access_router and core routers to confirm advertised routes for 10.200.0.0/24 and 20.200.0.0/24 and look for any route filtering or import/export rules.\n- Check host-based firewall settings on the web_server and backend_web hosts for selective ICMP/ICMP reply blocking.\n- Re-run targeted traceroutes and tcp-based connectivity tests (e.g., to TCP port 80 on backends) to confirm whether only ICMP is blocked or other traffic is also affected.\n\n(Per instructions I have not included mitigation steps — only detection, localization and root-cause reasoning.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 33533, "output_tokens": 3828, "total_tokens": 37361, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 3072}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2240}}}
